WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.922
This is Jacob's Research Journal. I'm Jacob Brooke. Today's deep

00:00:03.922 --> 00:00:07.843
dive: W-W-D-C twenty twenty-six — what's actually coming June eighth.

00:00:07.843 --> 00:00:11.765
Apple confirmed it two weeks ago: W-W-D-C twenty twenty-six runs

00:00:11.765 --> 00:00:15.686
June eighth through the twelfth, with the keynote kicking off

00:00:15.686 --> 00:00:19.608
Monday morning at Apple Park. On paper, it's the same

00:00:19.608 --> 00:00:23.529
format we've seen since twenty twenty — mostly online, a

00:00:23.529 --> 00:00:27.451
few thousand lottery winners in person, software betas by the

00:00:27.451 --> 00:00:31.373
afternoon. But the stakes this year are genuinely different. Last

00:00:31.373 --> 00:00:35.294
year, Apple spent W-W-D-C introducing Liquid Glass and playing catch-up

00:00:35.294 --> 00:00:39.216
on A-I promises that had been piling up since the

00:00:39.216 --> 00:00:43.137
original Apple Intelligence announcement at W-W-D-C twenty twenty-four. This year,

00:00:43.137 --> 00:00:47.059
the company has to prove that the billions it's spending

00:00:47.059 --> 00:00:50.980
on A-I infrastructure are producing something people actually want to

00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:54.902
use. And the centerpiece of that argument has a name

00:00:54.902 --> 00:00:58.824
you already know: Siri. I've spent the last week pulling

00:00:58.824 --> 00:01:02.745
together every credible source I can find — Bloomberg's Mark

00:01:02.745 --> 00:01:06.667
Gurman, Apple's own press materials, supply chain reporting, developer leaks,

00:01:06.667 --> 00:01:10.588
and community speculation — to build the most complete picture

00:01:10.588 --> 00:01:14.510
of what's coming. Let me walk you through it. Now

00:01:14.510 --> 00:01:18.431
let's talk about the main event: Siri's second act. If

00:01:18.431 --> 00:01:22.353
there's one story at W-W-D-C this year, it's Siri. And

00:01:22.353 --> 00:01:26.275
for the first time in Siri's fifteen-year existence, there's real

00:01:26.275 --> 00:01:30.196
reason to pay attention. In January, Apple and Google announced

00:01:30.196 --> 00:01:34.118
a multi-year partnership to build the next generation of Apple

00:01:34.118 --> 00:01:38.039
Foundation Models on Google's Gemini. Bloomberg's Gurman reported the deal

00:01:38.039 --> 00:01:41.961
is worth roughly one billion dollars per year. Let that

00:01:41.961 --> 00:01:45.882
sink in — that's not a licensing fee for a

00:01:45.882 --> 00:01:49.804
chat widget. That's infrastructure-level commitment. Apple is rebuilding its A-I

00:01:49.804 --> 00:01:53.725
backbone on Gemini, processed through its own Private Cloud Compute

00:01:53.725 --> 00:01:57.647
infrastructure so the company can keep its privacy story intact.

00:01:57.647 --> 00:02:01.569
The technical architecture is a two-tier system. Simple queries —

00:02:01.569 --> 00:02:05.490
about forty percent of interactions — are handled entirely by

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:09.412
a three-billion-parameter on-device model running on A-eighteen Pro and M-four

00:02:09.412 --> 00:02:13.333
chips, processing in under two hundred milliseconds without ever leaving

00:02:13.333 --> 00:02:17.255
the device. Complex queries requiring L-L-M level reasoning get routed

00:02:17.255 --> 00:02:21.176
to Apple's Private Cloud Compute servers, where Gemini models run

00:02:21.176 --> 00:02:25.098
in hardware-isolated, stateless environments. Google provides the intelligence; Apple controls

00:02:25.098 --> 00:02:29.020
the data pipeline. It's a clever arrangement that lets Apple

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:32.941
ship frontier A-I capability without abandoning its privacy positioning. But

00:02:32.941 --> 00:02:36.863
the bigger reveal expected at W-W-D-C is the chatbot version

00:02:36.863 --> 00:02:40.784
of Siri. According to MacRumors and multiple corroborating reports, Apple

00:02:40.784 --> 00:02:44.706
is building a full conversational interface — think ChatGPT or

00:02:44.706 --> 00:02:48.627
Claude — accessible via Siri's existing entry points: the wake

00:02:48.627 --> 00:02:52.549
word, the side button, or typing. The chatbot will feature

00:02:52.549 --> 00:02:56.471
persistent conversation history, web search, file analysis, image generation through

00:02:56.471 --> 00:03:00.392
Image Playground, and what Apple has been internally calling world

00:03:00.392 --> 00:03:04.314
knowledge capabilities. Here's a key detail worth calling out: Apple

00:03:04.314 --> 00:03:08.235
plans to open Siri to third-party A-I providers in i-O-S

00:03:08.235 --> 00:03:12.157
twenty-seven via an Extensions system in Settings. This ends OpenAI's

00:03:12.157 --> 00:03:16.078
exclusive arrangement and lets users direct queries to Claude, Gemini,

00:03:16.078 --> 00:03:20.000
Grok, and others — making Siri more of an A-I

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.922
router than a single model. That's a significant strategic shift.

00:03:23.922 --> 00:03:27.843
There's also the on-device intelligence layer. Siri is gaining personal

00:03:27.843 --> 00:03:31.765
context awareness — the ability to pull from your emails,

00:03:31.765 --> 00:03:35.686
messages, files, and photos to answer questions like "show me

00:03:35.686 --> 00:03:39.608
the files Eric sent me last week." Plus on-screen awareness,

00:03:39.608 --> 00:03:43.529
where Siri can see and act on whatever you're looking

00:03:43.529 --> 00:03:47.451
at. These features were originally promised for i-O-S eighteen and

00:03:47.451 --> 00:03:51.373
have been in various stages of development since. W-W-D-C twenty

00:03:51.373 --> 00:03:55.294
twenty-six is where they're supposed to actually ship. Now let's

00:03:55.294 --> 00:03:59.216
move on to i-O-S twenty-seven — the Snow Leopard strategy.

00:03:59.216 --> 00:04:03.137
Mark Gurman has been consistent on this one: i-O-S twenty-seven

00:04:03.137 --> 00:04:07.059
is a Snow Leopard update. If you remember the Mac

00:04:07.059 --> 00:04:10.980
O-S ten era, Snow Leopard followed the ambitious Leopard with

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:14.902
a release focused almost entirely on stability, performance, and cleaning

00:04:14.902 --> 00:04:18.824
up technical debt. No flashy features. Just making everything work

00:04:18.824 --> 00:04:22.745
better. That's exactly what i-O-S twenty-seven is shaping up to

00:04:22.745 --> 00:04:26.667
be. After i-O-S twenty-six introduced the biggest visual redesign since

00:04:26.667 --> 00:04:30.588
i-O-S seven with Liquid Glass, Apple's software engineers are reportedly

00:04:30.588 --> 00:04:34.510
spending this cycle eradicating bugs, replacing old code, and optimizing

00:04:34.510 --> 00:04:38.431
performance. The practical upshot: better battery life on older iPhones,

00:04:38.431 --> 00:04:42.353
smoother animations, fewer crashes, faster app launches. The kind of

00:04:42.353 --> 00:04:46.275
improvements that don't make for exciting keynote slides but make

00:04:46.275 --> 00:04:50.196
your phone feel noticeably better to use. That said, there

00:04:50.196 --> 00:04:54.118
are a few concrete feature additions worth tracking. Liquid Glass

00:04:54.118 --> 00:04:58.039
refinements — the new design language is reportedly getting a

00:04:58.039 --> 00:05:01.961
tuning pass, with MacRumors reporting a possible system-wide adjustment slider

00:05:01.961 --> 00:05:05.882
that would let users control the intensity of the translucency

00:05:05.882 --> 00:05:09.804
effects. If you've found Liquid Glass too busy, this could

00:05:09.804 --> 00:05:13.725
be the answer. Foldable iPhone groundwork — i-O-S twenty-seven is

00:05:13.725 --> 00:05:17.647
expected to include interfaces specifically designed for a larger foldable

00:05:17.647 --> 00:05:21.569
screen — side-by-side app support, new sidebar functionality, form-factor-specific layouts.

00:05:21.569 --> 00:05:25.490
The foldable iPhone itself isn't expected until the fall hardware

00:05:25.490 --> 00:05:29.412
event, but the software will be previewed at W-W-D-C. And

00:05:29.412 --> 00:05:33.333
there's a lower-confidence rumor about an A-I-powered Calendar app —

00:05:33.333 --> 00:05:37.255
likely smart scheduling suggestions and natural language event creation powered

00:05:37.255 --> 00:05:41.176
by Apple Intelligence. Now, for developers: Core A-I replaces Core

00:05:41.176 --> 00:05:45.098
M-L. This one flew under the mainstream radar but it's

00:05:45.098 --> 00:05:49.020
a big deal for the developer community. Apple is replacing

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:52.941
Core M-L with a new framework called Core A-I at

00:05:52.941 --> 00:05:56.863
W-W-D-C twenty twenty-six. The naming shift from M-L to A-I

00:05:56.863 --> 00:06:00.784
isn't just marketing — it signals a move from a

00:06:00.784 --> 00:06:04.706
framework designed primarily for running predictive models to one that

00:06:04.706 --> 00:06:08.627
supports conversational, generative, and agentic A-I systems. Core A-I is

00:06:08.627 --> 00:06:12.549
reportedly designed to help developers integrate third-party A-I models into

00:06:12.549 --> 00:06:16.471
their apps, with speculation that it may support the Model

00:06:16.471 --> 00:06:20.392
Context Protocol — or M-C-P — as a standardized integration

00:06:20.392 --> 00:06:24.314
layer. Core M-L isn't disappearing overnight — both frameworks will

00:06:24.314 --> 00:06:28.235
coexist during a transition period — but the direction is

00:06:28.235 --> 00:06:32.157
clear. Apple is building the plumbing for an ecosystem where

00:06:32.157 --> 00:06:36.078
every app can be A-I-powered, not just the ones Apple

00:06:36.078 --> 00:06:40.000
builds itself. Let's talk hardware at a software show. W-W-D-C

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.922
is a software event, but Apple has a habit of

00:06:43.922 --> 00:06:47.843
slipping hardware announcements in. This year, the main candidates are:

00:06:47.843 --> 00:06:51.765
Mac Studio with M-five Max and M-five Ultra. This is

00:06:51.765 --> 00:06:55.686
the most likely hardware announcement. The M-five Ultra would be

00:06:55.686 --> 00:06:59.608
Apple's first Ultra chip since the M-three generation, featuring up

00:06:59.608 --> 00:07:03.529
to an eighty-core G-P-U, Thunderbolt five, and up to ninety-six

00:07:03.529 --> 00:07:07.451
gigabytes of unified memory. For creative professionals and A-I developers

00:07:07.451 --> 00:07:11.373
running local models, this is the machine to watch. Mac

00:07:11.373 --> 00:07:15.294
mini with M-five and M-five Pro. A spec bump that

00:07:15.294 --> 00:07:19.216
would bring the full desktop lineup to the M-five generation.

00:07:19.216 --> 00:07:23.137
i-Mac with M-five. Rumored to include new color options alongside

00:07:23.137 --> 00:07:27.059
the chip upgrade. And the entry-level iPad with an A-eighteen

00:07:27.059 --> 00:07:30.980
chip, bringing Apple Intelligence capability to the cheapest iPad in

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:34.902
the lineup. Now, the HomePad question. Apple's rumored smart home

00:07:34.902 --> 00:07:38.824
display is the wildcard. Reports describe a seven-inch square touchscreen

00:07:38.824 --> 00:07:42.745
device with an A-eighteen chip, a TrueDepth camera with multi-user

00:07:42.745 --> 00:07:46.667
facial recognition, wall-mount and dock options, and deep HomeKit integration.

00:07:46.667 --> 00:07:50.588
Just two days ago, The Apple Post reported that the

00:07:50.588 --> 00:07:54.510
device is, quote, ready to ship. But here's the catch:

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:58.431
multiple sources report that the HomePad has been repeatedly delayed

00:07:58.431 --> 00:08:02.353
because Apple wants it to launch alongside the more capable

00:08:02.353 --> 00:08:06.275
version of Siri. If the chatbot Siri isn't ready until

00:08:06.275 --> 00:08:10.196
i-O-S twenty-seven ships in September, the HomePad likely gets a

00:08:10.196 --> 00:08:14.118
preview at W-W-D-C but doesn't actually go on sale until

00:08:14.118 --> 00:08:18.039
fall. Expected price: around three hundred and fifty dollars. Let

00:08:18.039 --> 00:08:21.961
me run through the confidence tiers quickly. Confirmed: i-O-S twenty-seven,

00:08:21.961 --> 00:08:25.882
mac-O-S twenty-seven, and the rest of the twenty-seven series will

00:08:25.882 --> 00:08:29.804
be previewed. That's from Apple's press release. Very high confidence:

00:08:29.804 --> 00:08:33.725
Gemini-powered Siri improvements, sourced from the Apple-Google joint statement and

00:08:33.725 --> 00:08:37.647
Bloomberg. Also very high: i-O-S twenty-seven as a Snow Leopard

00:08:37.647 --> 00:08:41.569
stability release, per Mark Gurman. High confidence: third-party A-I Extensions

00:08:41.569 --> 00:08:45.490
for Siri, Core A-I framework replacing Core M-L, the Siri

00:08:45.490 --> 00:08:49.412
chatbot interface debut, and Mac Studio with M-five Max and

00:08:49.412 --> 00:08:53.333
Ultra. Medium confidence: foldable iPhone software features, the HomePad preview,

00:08:53.333 --> 00:08:57.255
and the Liquid Glass adjustment slider. Lower confidence: A-I-powered Calendar

00:08:57.255 --> 00:09:01.176
app and a Siri visual redesign. So, what am I

00:09:01.176 --> 00:09:05.098
actually watching? Beyond the feature checklist, there are three meta-questions

00:09:05.098 --> 00:09:09.020
that will determine whether W-W-D-C twenty twenty-six is a pivotal

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:12.941
moment or just another Tuesday in Cupertino. First: does chatbot

00:09:12.941 --> 00:09:16.863
Siri actually feel competitive? Apple has spent over a billion

00:09:16.863 --> 00:09:20.784
dollars on the Gemini partnership and years of engineering. If

00:09:20.784 --> 00:09:24.706
the demo on June eighth shows a Siri that can

00:09:24.706 --> 00:09:28.627
hold a genuine conversation, search the web intelligently, remember context,

00:09:28.627 --> 00:09:32.549
and act across apps — if it feels like it

00:09:32.549 --> 00:09:36.471
belongs in the same conversation as ChatGPT and Claude —

00:09:36.471 --> 00:09:40.392
that changes Apple's A-I story completely. If it feels like

00:09:40.392 --> 00:09:44.314
a skin on top of Google's A-P-I with the usual

00:09:44.314 --> 00:09:48.235
Siri jank, that's a much bigger problem than any single

00:09:48.235 --> 00:09:52.157
feature miss. Second: how open is the Extensions system? The

00:09:52.157 --> 00:09:56.078
idea of routing Siri queries to third-party A-I providers is

00:09:56.078 --> 00:10:00.000
genuinely exciting. But the devil is in the implementation. Does

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.922
Extensions mean deep integration where Claude or Gemini can access

00:10:03.922 --> 00:10:07.843
your on-device context? Or does it mean a glorified web

00:10:07.843 --> 00:10:11.765
view that opens when Siri gives up? The difference between

00:10:11.765 --> 00:10:15.686
those two outcomes is the difference between Apple becoming the

00:10:15.686 --> 00:10:19.608
A-I platform and Apple being a gatekeeper that A-I companies

00:10:19.608 --> 00:10:23.529
have to work around. Third: is Core A-I a real

00:10:23.529 --> 00:10:27.451
framework or a rebrand? Apple has a mixed history with

00:10:27.451 --> 00:10:31.373
developer frameworks. Some, like SwiftUI, genuinely changed how people build

00:10:31.373 --> 00:10:35.294
apps. Others, like SiriKit, launched with fanfare and quietly stagnated.

00:10:35.294 --> 00:10:39.216
Core A-I needs to be in the first category. If

00:10:39.216 --> 00:10:43.137
it ships with real third-party model support and sensible A-P-Is,

00:10:43.137 --> 00:10:47.059
it could make every i-O-S app an A-I app within

00:10:47.059 --> 00:10:50.980
a year. Sixty-four days out. I'll be updating this analysis

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:54.902
as new information surfaces — and I'll be glued to

00:10:54.902 --> 00:10:58.824
the keynote livestream on June eighth. This is the year

00:10:58.824 --> 00:11:02.745
Apple has to prove its A-I strategy is real. No

00:11:02.745 --> 00:11:06.667
more coming later this year. The clock is running. That's

00:11:06.667 --> 00:11:10.588
the W-W-D-C twenty twenty-six preview deep dive. Full post and

00:11:10.588 --> 00:11:14.510
sources at jacob brooke ninety-five dot github dot i-o slash

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:16.863
jacobs research journal. Thanks for listening.
